image.altText: Aryna Sabalenka holds the Australian Open trophy.

props.synopsis: Aryna Sabalenka becomes the first back-to-back winner of the women's championship in 11 years following a straight-sets victory over Qinwen Zheng in the final. Follow live.

title.children: Sabalenka overpowers Zheng to defend Australian Open crown

image.altText: Matt Ebden and Rohan Bopanna celebrate winning the Australian Open

props.synopsis: Matt Ebden is the only Australian to lift a trophy at his home slam this year, winning the doubles alongside Indian veteran Rohan Bopanna.

title.children: Matt Ebden wins Australian Open men's doubles crown alongside 43yo Rohan Bopanna

image.altText: Doja Cat wearing a pink dress and knee high blue boots with hands positioned as if she's running

props.synopsis: The top 10 tracks from triple j's Hottest 100 of 2023 include songs from Doja Cat, G Flip and Dom Dolla. Here are your favourite songs of the year.

title.children: triple j has counted down the Hottest 100 songs of 2023. Here is your top 10 with hits from Doja Cat, G Flip and Troye Sivan

image.altText: Doja Cat poses at the Met Gala, an annual fundraising gala, dressed as a cat.

props.synopsis: triple j listeners have voted rapper Doja Cat into the number one spot of the Hottest 100 of 2023.

title.children: Doja Cat voted number one in triple j Hottest 100 of 2023 — as it happened

image.altText: Trump looks at camera as he is talking

props.synopsis: A US court awards writer and columnist E Jean Carroll more than $126 million in damages for a "storm of hate" caused by former president Donald Trump.

title.children: 'A huge defeat for every bully': Donald Trump ordered to pay $126 million in damages to writer he defamed

props.synopsis: One area that saw rain-induced flooding was Charters Towers, where emergency services rescued 14 people after they became trapped overnight.

title.children: Authorities rescue sightseers trapped by rising floodwaters, but is there more flooding to come?

image.altText: Cameron Green smiles as he holds the ball

props.synopsis: The Aussies had a totally normal one in the field, dropping chances and juggling others, while Shamar Joseph had his toe crushed by Mitch Starc. Here's the five quick hits from day three at the Gabba.

title.children: Five quick hits — a nasty injury and juggling catches

image.altText: Steve Smith watches the ball and prepares to hit it

props.synopsis: The West Indies set Australia 216 runs to win the second Test at the Gabba, with the tourists' innings coming to an end after tea on day three. Follow live.

title.children: Smith guides Australia to stumps on day three after steady start to run chase at the Gabba

image.altText: Two men at a desk with the word "Israel" written on a sign

props.synopsis: The International Court of Justice's ruling on South Africa's accusation that Israel is committing genocide against Palestinians is not a knockout victory for either side — and both are claiming victory, writes John Lyons.

title.children: As soon as the ruling was made on Gaza, both sides went into full media-management mode

image.altText: Two protesters stand outside the International Court of Justice holding the Palestinian flag

props.synopsis: Human rights groups are urging the federal government to take "concrete" steps to help prevent the genocide of Palestinians after the International Court of Justice's ruling that South Africa's allegation against Israel is "plausible".

title.children: Human rights groups say Australian government must act after ICJ ruling

image.altText: A house is blackened from fire, its roof partially destroyed

props.synopsis: Fire investigators are working to establish the cause of a blaze that damaged a Brisbane home overnight, which a witness said may have been sparked by an e-scooter battery.

title.children: Faulty scooter battery possible cause of fire that destroyed Brisbane home

image.altText: Homeless man Morgan sitting on a yoga mat with his cat around the Arts centre building near Melbourne CBD.

props.synopsis: How is Australia's increasingly cashless society affecting people experiencing homelessness? Experts say it has been a challenge for some rough sleepers.

title.children: Australia's transformation into a cashless society has left people like Morgan behind. Here's how they're coping

image.altText: Dozens of men dressed in black leaving the train station in North Sydney.

props.synopsis: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese and NSW Premier Chris Minns condemn the activity of the balaclava-clad group, with the premier considering outlawing the Nazi salute.

title.children: Prime minister 'horrified' by 'Neo-Nazi activity' in Sydney that sparked police incident

image.altText: A man climbing the Sydney Harbour Bridge.

props.synopsis: The employer of a fly-in fly-out worker found two days after crashing his work vehicle in remote Western Australia says the utility was due to have a tracking device installed next week.

title.children: Missing FIFO worker's vehicle was meant to have tracker installed next week

image.altText: An 18-year-old female sprinter crosses the line in first place, with a smile, wearing a top and sprinting shorts.

props.synopsis: Teenage sprint sensation Torrie Lewis claims the title of Australia's fastest-ever woman.

title.children: Torrie Lewis breaks women's 100m Australian record

image.altText: A TV still of Nicole Kidman standing on a Hong Kong street with a fearful expression. A shadowy figure is behind her.

props.synopsis: Expats may tell the story of three American women living in Hong Kong, but its true magic comes from telling the stories of the city's local community.

title.children: Nicole Kidman's swanky Hong Kong lifestyle comes to a tragic halt in new drama Expats

image.altText: A man in a suit speak from behind a lecturn while standing before two limp flags.

props.synopsis: Partial results from Tuvalu's national election suggests the pro-Taiwan leader of the Pacific islands nation, Kausea Natano, has lost his parliamentary seat.

title.children: Early election results point to Tuvalu's pro-Taiwan PM losing his seat

image.altText: Susan Neill-Fraser hugs a man on parliament lawns in Hobart

props.synopsis: Susan Neill-Fraser, who was convicted of murdering her partner Bob Chappell in 2009, attends a rally held by her supporters for the first time, but the conditions of her parole meant she could not address the crowd.

title.children: Convicted killer Susan Neill-Fraser attended a rally held by her supporters — but there was nothing she could say

image.altText: Vince McMahon in a suit and tie holding a microphone inside a wrestling ring with the WWE logo behind him

props.synopsis: US professional wrestling icon Vince McMahon resigns from World Wrestling Entertainment's parent company TKO the day after a former employee files a federal lawsuit accusing him and another former executive of serious sexual misconduct.

title.children: Vince McMahon resigns from WWE's parent company following sexual abuse allegations

image.altText: Diede de Groot holds the 2004 Australian Open trophy after winning the women's wheelchair singles final.

props.synopsis: Diede de Groot says she still has room for improvement after winning yet another Australian Open women's wheelchair singles title at Melbourne Park.

title.children: Dutch great de Groot claims sixth Australian Open and 21st major to extend winning streak to 135 matches

image.altText: Two teenage girl tennis players, one in green and one in yellow, pose with their trophies after a final

props.synopsis: Exciting 15-year-old prospect Emerson Jones, the daughter of Olympic medal-winning triathlete Loretta Harrop, finishes runner-up to Slovakian top seed Renata Jamrichova in the girls' final of the Australian Open.

title.children: Queenslander Emerson Jones finishes runner-up in Australian Open girls' final

image.altText: Image of big man with tall blonde wig next to a drawing of a big man with tall blonde hair

props.synopsis: If he is not in his Ambulance Victoria uniform, Phil Bell is dressed as his favourite anime character and pulling 4WDs and boats along the streets of his country town, a gentle "circus freak" in pursuit of a big dream.

title.children: Paramedic Phil 'Teddy Bear' Bell consumes 5,000 calories a day and a lot of anime chasing one strong ambition

image.altText: Primary aged school stduents with school logo green backpacks walk along a city street

props.synopsis: My son, along with tens of thousands of other Australian kids, is about to formally leave the land of childhood and go to secondary school next week, and a clean-out of many of his kindergarten things felt long overdue, writes Virginia Trioli.

title.children: My son is preparing for high school by hardly talking about it. I'm whispering to friends, hiding out of earshot

image.altText: The view of a coastal town settled on a crescent-shaped bay.

props.synopsis: Apollo Bay is a tourist mecca whose population explodes roughly 10 times in the peak visitor season. But locals and workers without deep pockets say they're struggling to stay, exacerbating the pressures on those who remain year-round.

title.children: The picturesque Australian town where locals can’t afford to live

image.altText: Two men crouch beside black foam pieces that are floating in ankle-deep water

props.synopsis: Sea rangers hope an artificial floating roost made from oyster farm "pillows" will help provide vital habitat for endangered shorebirds.

title.children: How oyster shells, foam and zip ties are offering a critical life raft for declining shorebird populations

image.altText: The bomb blast scene in Kuta several days after the bomb blasts.

props.synopsis: Two Malaysian men, who have been in US custody since 2003, are sentenced to 23 years in confinement over their roles in the 2002 Bali bombings — but a pre-trial deal means they will serve less than six years of their sentences.

title.children: Guantanamo Bay detainees apologise, show 'torture' drawings before Bali bombing sentences handed down

image.altText: Peter Dutton speaks in a courtyard at Parliament House

props.synopsis: Anthony Albanese, in Peter Dutton's view, has committed the gravest of all political sins. But something can be a "broken promise" and also be the right decision for the times, writes Matthew Doran.

title.children: Dutton is the king of the wedge — but will his crazy brave calculation misfire?

image.altText: A woman in deep red evening gown and immaculate, sleek hair and makeup smiles as she raises two hands into prayer position

props.synopsis: When Thai media mogul Anne Jakkaphong Jakrajutatip bought the Miss Universe competition, she promised to transform the beauty pageant. But just a year later, the business is struggling to survive amid claims of rigging, sexual harassment and financial woes.

title.children: When a trans icon bought Miss Universe, she promised to reform it for the next generation. A year later, she's sold half of it
